**On January 16 ,2023, the Government of Japan donated US$130 million to :abbr[WFP] to support 37 countries across Asia, the Middle East, and Africa amid the global hunger crisis.**\
\
The funds included:
- US$19.1 million for emergency food assistance in Ukraine;
- US$12.4 million for emergency food and nutrition assistance to those affected by climate shocks in Afghanistan;
- US$13.9 million for humanitarian needs in Myanmar;
- US$5 million for emergency food assistance in schools in Somalia;
- US$3.9 million for life-saving nutritional treatment for children and women in Ethiopia; and
- US$6.6 million for vulnerable people in Yemen.
The remainder of the donation was allocated across several countries in the regions.

**An international “Standing with the Ukrainian People” conference, jointly organized by France and Ukraine in Paris on December 13, 2022 mobilized €1 billion (US$1.1 billion) in humanitarian assistance to Ukraine.**\
\
The conference, co-chaired by French President Emmanuel Macron and the President of Ukraine Volodymyr Zelensky, represented by his Prime Minister. Approximately 70 high-level participants represented the main states and international organizations partnering with Ukraine.\
\
The conference resulted in pledges from donors totaling over €1 billion (US$1.1 billion), which will be allocated to:
- €415 million (US$442 million) to support Ukraine's energy sector;
- €25 million (US$27 million) for water;
- €28 million (US$30 million) for food security;
- €17 million (US$18 million ) for shoring up healthcare facilities and infrastructure; 
- €22 million (US$23 million) for repairs to transportation infrastructure; and
- A remaining €493 million (US$518 million) which has yet to be allocated.

<br>

A coordination mechanism is planned to be set up to monitor the effective implementation of pledges and the assessment of the priority needs expressed by Ukraine in the fields of electricity and energy, water, food, healthcare, and transport sectors.

**On November 26, 2022, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky announced the 'Grain from Ukraine Initiative,' which seeks to facilitate the delivery of 125,000 tons of grain to nations facing food insecurity and famine, including Yemen and Sudan, among others.**\
\
Ukraine presented the program at the G20 meeting in November 2022. The initiative aims to send up to 60 shipments of grain to low-income countries in Africa and provide food for at least 5 million people by summer 2023. Zelensky officially launched the initiative on the 90th anniversary of the Holodomor, a famine inflicted on Ukrainians by Joseph Stalin’s Soviet Union.\
\
The announcement was accompanied by pledges from donor countries, including:
- Canada: CA$30 million (US$22 million) via the World Food Programme (WFP);
- France: US$20 million;
- The Netherlands: US$4 million via the WFP;
- Sweden: SEK 100 million (US$10 million) via the WFP;
- The US: US$20 million; and
- The UK: US$6 million.

<br>

In total, the initiative raised more than US$150 million and received support from more than 20 countries.

On October 17, 2022, UNICEF published a new study, entitled 'The impact of the war in Ukraine and subsequent economic downturn on child poverty in Eastern Europe and Central Asia,' which found an additional 4 million children in Eastern Europe and Central Asia are living in poverty, a 19% increase from 2021.
\
The report compared data from 22 countries in the region and found that children bear the brunt of the impact of the economic crisis caused by the war in Ukraine. 
\
The study also showed that the consequences of child poverty extend beyond families in economic distress. The sharp increase of children living in poverty could lead to 4,500 more children dying before their first birthday, and the losses in learning could equate to 117,000 more children dropping out of school in 2022.
\
The study developed a set of recommendations to help reduce the number of children living in poverty, including:
\
- Provision of universal cash benefits for children and a guaranteed minimum income;
- Extension of social assistance benefits to all families with children in need, including refugees;
- Protection of social spending, especially for the most vulnerable children and families;
- Protection and support for health, nutrition, and social assistance services to pregnant mothers, infants, and preschool children;

On September 7, 2022, the European Third Sector Forum, composed of more than 101 Italian CSOs, organized a panel with representatives from all political parties running for national elections on September 25, 2022.
\
During the meeting, CSOs presented a six-point action plan to revamp social policy, prioritizing a more robust welfare state, reducing inequality, a novel approach to foreign policy and development cooperation, and new investment in human and social capital. The plan consisted of six main action points:
\
Tackling multidimensional poverty and socio-economic inequalities by investing in education and health systems;
Investing in equitable energy- and digital transitions;
Supporting welfare systems, especially the National Recovery and Resilience Plan;
Preserving peace by immediately stopping the war in Ukraine and increasing resources for development cooperation by meeting the 0.7% ODA/GNI target by 2030;
Boosting cohesion and citizen participation, through programs to involve 100,000 younger citizens to take part in the national volunteer civil service; and
Empowering CSOs of all sizes through government spending.
The CSOs asserted that these measures would be crucial to supporting the transition towards a more equitable country. CSOs play an outsized role in Italy, employing more than 860,000 workers and engaging over 5 million volunteers, and are crucial to realizing new models of socio-economic development based on social cohesion and innovation. 
\

Japan announced an additional US$200 million in response to the global food crisis caused by the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
\
The government will provide food assistance and capacity building for countries facing shortages, disburse emergency food assistance to countries in the Middle East and Africa, and support grain exports from Ukraine. The funds will be donated through UN agencies and Japanese NGOs. Specifically: 
\
*   US$47 million will be disbursed bilaterally for food assistance and capacity building for food production;
*   US$36 million will be channeled through the World Food Programme (WFP) and will go toward food assistance and capacity building for food production;
*   US$20 million will go to the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and will target capacity building for food production;
*   US$68 million will be allocated to the WFP and will go to emergency food and nutrition assistance;
*   US$5 million will be channeled through the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East (UNRWA) and will be disbursed as emergency food assistance; 
*   US$17 million will go to the FAO will support the promotion of grain exports from Ukraine; and 
*   US$10 million for Japanese NGOs (through Japan Platform) will target emergency food assistance. 
\
